Negative Test Cases Performed
1) Authentication tests
Case A — Login with empty username and password

Input: empty login form
Expected behavior: system should reject login and show a validation or authentication error
Risk if not handled: invalid login requests can reach backend unnecessarily and confuse the user

Case B — Login with wrong password

Input: valid username + incorrect password
Expected behavior: clear “invalid credentials” style response without exposing technical details
Risk if not handled: users may not understand why login failed, or backend may leak unnecessary information

Case C — Access protected employee/salary routes without login

Input: request protected route directly without authenticated session
Expected behavior: request should be rejected with unauthorized response
Risk if not handled: unauthorized users may access or modify payroll-related data

2) Employee creation / update tests
Case D — Create employee with missing required fields

Input: submit employee form without one or more required values
Expected behavior: validation error and no employee should be created
Risk if not handled: incomplete employee records may enter payroll flow and cause downstream salary issues

Case E — Create or update employee with negative salary

Input: salary = -1000
Expected behavior: validation should reject the request
Risk if not handled: invalid salary data can be stored and affect payroll calculations or salary reports

Case F — Create or update employee with salary = 0

Input: salary = 0
Expected behavior: system should either reject it or clearly support it only if the business rule allows it
Risk if not handled: a payroll operator may accidentally save zero salary and generate incorrect salary output

Case G — Create employee with extremely large salary value

Input: salary = 999999999
Expected behavior: system should validate range and reject unrealistic values if business rules require it
Risk if not handled: outlier values can break payroll reports, dashboards, or salary calculations

Case H — Submit employee form twice quickly

Input: double-click save / repeated request
Expected behavior: duplicate creation should be prevented
Risk if not handled: duplicate employee or duplicate salary records may be created

3) Input integrity / malformed payload tests
Case I — Send invalid data type in salary field

Input: salary = "abc" instead of number
Expected behavior: backend should reject invalid type with validation error
Risk if not handled: malformed data may cause runtime errors or invalid database records

Case J — Send payload with missing fields directly to API

Input: incomplete JSON body
Expected behavior: backend should reject request with meaningful error
Risk if not handled: system may fail unpredictably or save partial data

Case K — Long text / special characters in name or designation fields

Input: very long string or special characters
Expected behavior: system should handle safely without crashing or corrupting data
Risk if not handled: broken UI rendering, database issues, or unsafe content storage

Case L — Script injection string in text field

Input: <script>alert('x')</script>
Expected behavior: system should safely reject, sanitize, or store safely without execution
Risk if not handled: stored XSS or unsafe rendering in admin pages

Five Most Critical Failures to Automate

The following failures are the most important to automate because they directly protect salary and employee data:

1. Reject unauthenticated access to protected employee/salary actions

Why critical: prevents unauthorized payroll or employee data access

2. Reject negative salary values

Why critical: prevents obviously invalid payroll data from entering the system

3. Reject employee creation with missing required fields

Why critical: prevents incomplete employee records from reaching payroll workflows

4. Reject malformed salary type input

Why critical: protects backend and data integrity from invalid payloads

5. Prevent duplicate employee creation / repeated submit behavior

Why critical: avoids duplicate records that can later create payroll confusion

Observations and Risk Summary

The most important pattern in negative testing for this HRMS is weak validation at the boundary of payroll data. If the system allows invalid employee or salary information to enter the database, the problem may not appear immediately on the same screen. Instead, it can surface later during salary review, payroll generation, or reporting — when the cost of correction is much higher.

That is why negative testing in this HRMS should focus less on cosmetic form behavior and more on whether invalid data can cross the system boundary and affect payroll-related records.

Recommended Negative Test Automation Scope

I would automate negative tests for:

protected route access
salary validation
employee required-field validation
malformed API payload rejection
duplicate create / repeated submit protection

I would keep broader exploratory negative testing manual for low-risk UI behaviors and uncommon visual edge cases, because those are lower business risk than payroll-data integrity failures.
